Here is a simple implementation of the library management system in Java:

```java
import java.util.*;

class Book {
    private String id;
    private String title;
    private boolean borrowed;

    public Book(String id, String title) {
        this.id = id;
        this.title = title;
        this.borrowed = false;
    }

    public String getId() {
        return id;
    }

    public String getTitle() {
        return title;
    }

    public void borrowBook() {
        borrowed = true;
    }

    public void returnBook() {
        borrowed = false;
    }

    public boolean isBorrowed() {
        return borrowed;
    }
}

class Member {
    private String memberId;
    private List<Book> borrowedBooks;

    public Member(String memberId) {
        this.memberId = memberId;
        this.borrowedBooks = new ArrayList<>();
    }

    public String getMemberId() {
        return memberId;
    }

    public void borrowBook(Book book) {
        borrowedBooks.add(book);
        book.borrowBook();
    }

    public void returnBook(Book book) {
        borrowedBooks.remove(book);
        book.returnBook();
    }
}

class Library {
    private Map<String, Book> books;
    private Map<String, Member> members;

    public Library() {
        books = new HashMap<>();
        members = new HashMap<>();
    }

    public void addBook(Book book) {
        books.put(book.getId(), book);
    }

    public void removeBook(String bookId) {
        if (books.containsKey(bookId)) {
            books.remove(bookId);
        } else {
            System.out.println("The book does not exist");
        }
    }

    public void issueBook(String memberId, String bookId) {
        if (!members.containsKey(memberId)) {
            System.out.println("The member does not exist");
            return;
        }
        if (!books.containsKey(bookId)) {
            System.out.println("The book does not exist");
            return;
        }
        if (books.get(bookId).isBorrowed()) {
            System.out.println("The book is already borrowed");
            return;
        }
        members.get(memberId).borrowBook(books.get(bookId));
    }

    public void returnBook(String memberId, String bookId) {
        if (!members.containsKey(memberId)) {
            System.out.println("The member does not exist");
            return;
        }
        if (!books.containsKey(bookId)) {
            System.out.println("The book does not exist");
            return;
        }
        members.get(memberId).returnBook(books.get(bookId));
    }

    public boolean checkAvailability(String bookId) {
        if (!books.containsKey(bookId)) {
            System.out.println("The book does not exist");
            return false;
        }
        return !books.get(bookId).isBorrowed();
    }
}
```

In this code, we have three classes: `Book`, `Member` and `Library`. The `Book` class represents a book with an ID, title and borrowed status. The `Member` class represents a library member with an ID and a list of borrowed books. The `Library` class manages all the books and members.

This is a very basic version of a library management system. In a real-world application, you would need to handle more complex scenarios such as multiple copies of the same book, due dates for borrowed books, fines for late returns, etc.

