Here is a simple implementation of a circular linked list in Java. This class supports adding elements, removing elements and rotating the list by n positions.

```java
public class CircularLinkedList {
    Node last;

    static class Node {
        int data;
        Node next;

        Node(int data) {
            this.data = data;
        }
    }

    public void add(int data) {
        Node newNode = new Node(data);

        if (last == null) {
            last = newNode;
            last.next = last;
        } else {
            newNode.next = last.next;
            last.next = newNode;
            last = newNode;
        }
    }

    public void remove(int key) {
        if (last == null)
            return;

        Node prev = last, temp = last.next;
        do {
            if (temp.data == key) {
                if (temp == last)
                    last = prev;
                prev.next = temp.next;
                return;
            }
            prev = temp;
            temp = temp.next;
        } while (temp != last.next);
    }

    public void rotate(int k) {
        if (k == 0 || last == null)
            return;

        Node current = last.next;
        for (int i = 0; i < k - 1; i++)
            current = current.next;

        last = current;
    }

    public void printList() {
        if (last == null)
            return;

        Node temp = last.next;
        do {
            System.out.print(temp.data + " ");
            temp = temp.next;
        } while (temp != last.next);
        System.out.println();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        CircularLinkedList list = new CircularLinkedList();

        // Adding elements to the list
        list.add(10);
        list.add(20);
        list.add(30);
        list.add(40);
        list.add(50);

        // Printing the list
        list.printList();  // Output: 10 20 30 40 50

        // Removing an element from the list
        list.remove(30);

        // Printing the list after removal
        list.printList();  // Output: 10 20 40 50

        // Rotating the list by 2 positions
        list.rotate(2);

        // Printing the list after rotation
        list.printList();  // Output: 40 50 10 20
    }
}
```

In this code, `Node` is a static inner class that represents each node in the circular linked list. The `CircularLinkedList` class maintains a reference to the last node in the list (`last`). The `add(int)` method adds a new node at the end of the list. The `remove(int)` method removes the first occurrence of a node with the given value. The `rotate(int)` method rotates the list clockwise by the specified number of positions. The `printList()` method prints all the elements in the list starting from the first node.

