In this example, we will create a simple C++ application that demonstrates the use of smart pointers to manage memory allocation and deallocation for custom classes. We will create a `Person` class and use `std::shared_ptr` and `std::unique_ptr` to manage instances of this class.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
#include <string>

class Person {
public:
    Person(const std::string& name) : name_(name) {
        std::cout << "Person constructor called for " << name_ << std::endl;
    }

    ~Person() {
        std::cout << "Person destructor called for " << name_ << std::endl;
    }

    void sayHello() const {
        std::cout << "Hello, my name is " << name_ << std::endl;
    }

private:
    std::string name_;
};

void sharedPtrExample() {
    std::cout << "Shared pointer example:" << std::endl;

    std::shared_ptr<Person> alice = std::make_shared<Person>("Alice");
    alice->sayHello();

    {
        std::shared_ptr<Person> bob = std::make_shared<Person>("Bob");
        bob->sayHello();
    } // Bob's destructor will be called here since its reference count goes to 0

    alice->sayHello(); // Alice is still alive
} // Alice's destructor will be called here since its reference count goes to 0

void uniquePtrExample() {
    std::cout << "\nUnique pointer example:" << std::endl;

    std::unique_ptr<Person> carol = std::make_unique<Person>("Carol");
    carol->sayHello();

    {
        std::unique_ptr<Person> dave = std::make_unique<Person>("Dave");
        dave->sayHello();
    } // Dave's destructor will be called here since it goes out of scope

    carol->sayHello(); // Carol is still alive
} // Carol's destructor will be called here since it goes out of scope

int main() {
    sharedPtrExample();
    uniquePtrExample();

    return 0;
}
```

When you run this application, the output should look like:

```
Shared pointer example:
Person constructor called for Alice
Hello, my name is Alice
Person constructor called for Bob
Hello, my name is Bob
Person destructor called for Bob
Hello, my name is Alice
Person destructor called for Alice

Unique pointer example:
Person constructor called for Carol
Hello, my name is Carol
Person constructor called for Dave
Hello, my name is Dave
Person destructor called for Dave
Hello, my name is Carol
Person destructor called for Carol
```

This demonstrates how smart pointers can automatically manage memory allocation and deallocation for custom classes. In this case, `std::shared_ptr` allows multiple instances to share ownership of a single object, while `std::unique_ptr` ensures that only one instance owns the object at any given time. When the last owner of an object (either a `shared_ptr` or a `unique_ptr`) goes out of scope or is reset, the object's destructor is automatically called, ensuring proper cleanup of resources.

