Here's a Java program that reads a text file containing lines of space-separated integers, computes the sum of the integers for each line, and prints it out. The program also handles cases where the file does not exist or contains invalid data.

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.File;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.io.IOException;

public class SumIntegersFromFile {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Replace with your desired file path
        String filePath = "input.txt";

        try {
            File file = new File(filePath);
            FileReader fileReader = new FileReader(file);
            BufferedReader bufferedReader = new BufferedReader(fileReader);

            String line;
            while ((line = bufferedReader.readLine()) != null) {
                int sum = computeSum(line);
                if (sum != Integer.MIN_VALUE) {
                    System.out.println("Sum: " + sum);
                } else {
                    System.out.println("Invalid data in line: " + line);
                }
            }

            bufferedReader.close();
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.err.println("Error reading file: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }

    private static int computeSum(String line) {
        String[] numbers = line.split(" ");
        int sum = 0;

        for (String number : numbers) {
            try {
                sum += Integer.parseInt(number);
            } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
                return Integer.MIN_VALUE;
            }
        }

        return sum;
    }
}
```

To use this program, replace `filePath` with the path to your input file. The program will read the file line by line, compute the sum of integers on each line, and print the result. If the file does not exist or contains invalid data, an error message will be printed.

```java
public class StackArray {
    private int maxSize;
    private int top;
    private int[] stackArray;

    public StackArray(int size) {
        maxSize = size;
        stackArray = new int[maxSize];
        top = -1;
    }

    public void push(int value) {
        if (isFull()) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Stack is full. Cannot push onto the stack.");
        }
        stackArray[++top] = value;
    }

    public int pop() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Stack is empty. Cannot pop from the stack.");
        }
        return stackArray[top--];
    }

    public int peek() {
        if (isEmpty()) {
            throw new RuntimeException("Stack is empty. Cannot peek at the stack.");
        }
        return stackArray[top];
    }

    public boolean isEmpty() {
        return (top == -1);
    }

    public boolean isFull() {
        return (top + 1 == maxSize);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        StackArray stack = new StackArray(5);

        System.out.println("Pushing elements onto the stack:");
        stack.push(10);
        stack.push(20);
        stack.push(30);
        stack.push(40);
        stack.push(50);

        try {
            stack.push(60);
        } catch (RuntimeException e) {
            System.out.println(e.getMessage());
        }

        System.out.println("Peeking at the top element: " + stack.peek());

        System.out.println("Popping elements from the stack:");
        System.out.println(stack.pop());
        System.out.println(stack.pop());
        System.out.println(stack.pop());
        System.out.println(stack.pop());
        System.out.println(stack.pop());

        try {
            stack.pop();
        } catch (RuntimeException e) {
            System.out.println(e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

This Java program implements a stack data structure using an array with push, pop, and peek methods. The stack has a fixed size and throws an exception when trying to push onto a full stack or pop from an empty stack.

